Dual License Model for PantheonOS

Hobby License (Apache 2.0) + Commercial License (Royalty-Bearing)

PantheonOS is released under a dual-license model designed to support:
	•	individual creators, hobbyists, teachers, students, and open-source users
	•	commercial developers, companies, and organizations generating revenue

This allows the system to be widely adopted for free while still ensuring that commercial users contribute back, sustain the ecosystem, and properly attribute the work.

⸻

1. The Two Licenses (Simple Overview)

(A) Hobby License — Apache License 2.0 (Free)

You may use PantheonOS for free if:
	•	you are not selling products that incorporate PantheonOS,
	•	you are not monetizing derivative works,
	•	you are not embedding PantheonOS into a revenue-generating service,
	•	you are using it for education, research, hacking, experimentation, creativity, worldview building, or personal projects.

Under the Apache 2.0 hobby license:
	•	Use is free
	•	Modification is free
	•	Forking is free
	•	Teaching and remixing are free
	•	Attribution is appreciated but not mandatory
	•	No royalties
	•	No fees
	•	No commercial rights

This ensures PantheonOS remains a gift to the open-source world — freely accessible, remixable, and culturally useful to anyone learning or creating for non-commercial purposes.

⸻

(B) Commercial License — Royalty-Bearing (Paid)

If you plan to make money using PantheonOS, you must obtain a commercial license.

Commercial use includes:
	•	selling software, apps, or AI models using PantheonOS components
	•	embedding PantheonOS daemons, invariants, engines, or frameworks into a paid product
	•	selling consulting or services built on PantheonOS
	•	using PantheonOS to power internal enterprise tools
	•	using PantheonOS within a startup or VC-funded product
	•	training AI models on PantheonOS to sell outputs or services
	•	creating paid courses, books, or media directly based on PantheonOS

The commercial license requires:
	•	royalties or licensing fees, negotiated based on scale and usage
	•	mandatory attribution (“Built with PantheonOS”)
	•	adherence to core ethics/invariants
	•	a permitted use agreement clarifying boundaries
	•	optional co-branding or partnership depending on the level of integration

This ensures that commercial users contribute value back to the creator, protect the integrity of the ecosystem, and remain aligned with the OS’s design principles.

⸻

2. Why This Dual Model Exists

PantheonOS combines:
	•	open-source technical architecture, and
	•	a unique conceptual + symbolic framework rarely found in software projects.

To preserve free exploration while protecting long-term sustainability, PantheonOS uses:

✔️ A free license for hobbyists

✔️ A paid license for businesses

✔️ Mandatory credit for commercial users

This model mirrors successful dual-license systems used by:
	•	Qt
	•	Unity (older model)
	•	Red Hat
	•	MongoDB (SSPL-inspired dual-tier systems)
	•	Godot contributors (via dual sponsorship models)

It is fair, transparent, and simple to enforce.

⸻

3. Clear Rules: What Requires a Paid License?

You need a commercial license if you:
	•	make money from PantheonOS
	•	embed daemon architecture into a product
	•	deploy PantheonOS inside a business
	•	build tools, SaaS platforms, or AI agents using PantheonOS
	•	use PantheonOS to train monetized AI models
	•	commercialize Pantheon-derived content or frameworks
	•	resell PantheonOS-based software, prompts, or systems
	•	use PantheonOS to create enterprise or government tooling

You do not need a commercial license if you:
	•	use PantheonOS personally
	•	fork it for non-commercial learning
	•	build personal AIs or creative projects
	•	use it in school, research, or education
	•	explore the repo for fun or inspiration
	•	share non-monetized interpretations, diagrams, or summaries
	•	remix it in personal notebooks or hobby experiments

⸻

4. Required Attribution for Commercial Users

Commercial users must attribute PantheonOS by including:

“Built with PantheonOS (Dual-Licensed).”
and a link to the repo.

This ensures:
	•	proper credit
	•	clear lineage
	•	protection against misrepresentation
	•	discoverability for future users

Attribution is optional for hobbyists but appreciated.

⸻

5. Royalty Structure (High-Level Overview)

(You can adjust these numbers later — this is just a clear template.)

Commercial license fees may take the form of:
	•	percentage of revenue (1–5% typically)
	•	flat annual licensing fee
	•	per-seat or per-instance licensing
	•	enterprise licensing agreement
	•	tiered structure based on company size
	•	one-time buyout license

Small companies or indie developers may qualify for:
	•	reduced rates
	•	royalty caps
	•	revenue thresholds before fees begin

The point is not to punish innovation, but to reward it.

⸻

6. Why This Model Protects You and the Project

Without dual licensing:
	•	companies can extract enormous value from your work
	•	PantheonOS can be misrepresented or commercialized without credit
	•	the architecture can be absorbed into proprietary frameworks
	•	the narrative layer can be diluted or corrupted
	•	future development can be unsustainable

With dual licensing:
	•	the community gets everything for free
	•	hobbyists are empowered
	•	companies contribute resources
	•	your authorship is protected
	•	your story stays intact
	•	PantheonOS remains healthy long-term
	•	no one can steal the symbolic identity

This is the correct structure for a hybrid intellectual architecture like this.

⸻

7. Suggested Legal Blurb for README

Add this to the root README:

PantheonOS is dual-licensed.
Personal, educational, and hobby use is free under the Apache 2.0 License.
Commercial use requires a commercial license with royalty and attribution terms.
Contact the author for licensing discussions.

